</ul>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Causes of Cold</h2>



<p>Here are the main causes:</p>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Viral Infection:</strong> The Common Cold is caused by over 200 virus strains, with the rhinovirus topping the list. Other viruses that lead to colds include coronaviruses, adenoviruses, and enteroviruses. These viruses penetrate through the mouth, eyes, or nose or contact with tainted surfaces, such as doorknobs, if an infected person coughs or sneezes while speaking.</li>



<li><strong>Transmission Methods:</strong> Colds are highly contagious illnesses that can quickly pass between individuals. The primary modes of transmission include:</li>



<li><strong>Airborne Droplets:</strong> If an infected person sneezes or coughs, other people in the same area may breathe in these droplets.</li>



<li><strong>Direct Contact: </strong>Holding or touching a person with a cold is a mechanism through which the virus may be transferred to your hands and face.</li>



<li><strong>Contaminated Surfaces: </strong>Information about viruses exposed that they can remain alive on the existing surfaces for some time. If you touch some objects, such as a doorknob, a light switch, or shared cutlery, and then proceed to touch your face, they may spread the disease.</li>



<li><strong>Seasonal Factors:</strong> Flu is particularly widespread in the autumn and winter because people are together more often when they are at home. This leads to increased contact that helps spread flu or cold viruses and other illnesses within schools.</li>



<li><strong>Age and Health Status:</strong> Colds are common in children because their immune systems are still developing and because they spend most of their time in settings such as schools or daycare centers. Also, people who suffer from a compromised immune system or have some systemic diseases can become infected with colds more easily.</li>



<li><strong>Environmental Factors:</strong> Cold and dry air, such as that during winter because of heaters, prevents much of the lining of the nose and throat from being moisturized, which makes it probable that the virus will advance.</li>



<li><strong>Lifestyle Factors:</strong> Second-hand smoking and smoking can make people prone to catching the flu by initially causing inflammation of the respiratory system and, secondly, by lowering the body’s immunity to ailments.</li>
</ul>



